<TEXT>
the investigation of the deadly southeastern mail 
bombings continues like mad a civil rights leader says but 
with a much lower profile since the day agents searched a septic 
tank as tv cameras rolled 
the fbi wont say whether there have been any developments in 
the probe of the bombings that killed a federal judge and a civil 
rights attorney and there have been few signs of progress in the 
case now more than 100 days old 
theres nothing new here fbi spokesman carlos fernandez 
said recently in washington the investigation is ongoing but as 
far as any specifics no one can get into that 
hundreds of federal agents have participated in the 
investigation three men were subjected to extensive searches and 
media scrutiny but no one has been identified as a suspect 
naacp southeast regional director earl shinhoster who has 
received regular briefings on the case said he doesnt feel its 
near being solved 
my own view is theyre as close as they were in december 
said shinhoster but he said hes satisfied the government hasnt 
decreased its investigative effort 
they are on this case like mad he said 
the dec 1619 bombings killed 11th us circuit court of 
appeals judge robert s vance at his mountain brook ala home and 
savannah ga alderman robert robinson who had done legal work 
for the national advancement of colored people 
bombs were intercepted at the 11th circuit courthouse in atlanta 
and the naacp office in jacksonville fla 
followup letters indicated the motivation for the attacks was 
racism and threatened further violence 
shinhoster said the search for the typewriter used to write the 
letters continues to be a main focus of the investigation 
i think the person who finds that typewriter will be given 5 
million he joked 
fbi agents with reporters close behind swarmed over 
enterprise ala on jan 22 and searched property of the probes 
first apparent target junk shop owner robert wayne oferrell they 
apparently came up empty 
there still are some fbi agents in the small town said fbi 
spokesman doug marshall 
oferrell who wrote letters criticizing the appeals court after 
losing a workers compensation case is one of the three who have 
come under the most scrutiny 
the others are brian joseph fleming an enterprise print shop 
owner previously indicted on gunrunning charges with business ties 
to oferrell and walter leroy moody jr a selfemployed literary 
consultant from rex ga who was convicted in a 1972 bomb case 
oferrell said that since testifying before a grand jury in 
birmingham ala on march 6 he has had only one contact with 
authorities 
they returned some of my merchandise and paperwork they 
carried off he said tax papers stuff like that 
i just kind of assume theyll keep a low profile until they 
arrest someone and then theyll leave me alone he said 
