<TEXT>
voters in this college town on monday 
approved a token 5 fine on abortion should the procedure be 
banned and a fivefold increase in the citys 5 marijuana penalty 
with all 63 precincts counted the abortion proposal declaring 
ann arbor a zone of reproductive freedom passed 15698 to 
8578 said deputy clerk yvonne carl 
the proposal to raise the fine for possessing marijuana from 5 
to 25 was approved 12901 to 11419 carl said 
local and statewide elections were scheduled for tuesday in 
three other states 
despite media attention surrounding the proposals carl said 
most residents were concerned about a 28 million bond proposal to 
fund landfills and launch a major recycling program in the city 
carl said 
thats the one that will affect our daily way of living she 
said the proposal passed 18866 to 5601 
about twice as many voters as usual turned out for municipal 
elections to cast ballots on 13 city council candidates for five 
seats and six proposals including the abortion rights and 
marijuana fine questions officials said 
the estimated 33 percent turnout was considerably higher than 
the citys normal election turnout of 15 percent to 18 percent 
said city clerk winifred northcross 
the abortion measure known as proposal c amends the citys 
charter by imposing a fine similar to a parking ticket should 
federal or state law ever restrict abortion who would pay the fine 
would depend on how the penalty was stated in the federal or state 
law 
the marijuana measure or proposal b was put on the ballot by 
the council the 5 fine for possession and sale of marijuana was 
adopted in 1972 and reinstated in 1974 after republicans repealed 
it 
opponents of the small fine said the minor penalty has created a 
perception of the city as being a haven for drugs 
carl said earlier it was difficult to predict how many of the 
25000 students at the university of michigan would vote but 
backers of the abortion provision counted on student support 
a good turnout means to us that well win and its up all over 
town said sabra briere coordinator of the effort to place the 
abortion measure on the ballot 
right to life of michigan has not opposed the provision 
concentrating on its statewide drive to gather signatures 
initiating a measure requiring that girls 17 and younger obtain a 
parents consent for abortion 
republican members of the ann arbor city council opposed the 
charter provision maintaining it will clutter up the charter and 
was designed to draw democratic voters to the polls to help elect 
democratic candidates 
the supreme court has already relegated this issue back to the 
states and thats where it belongs not on a local community 
level said ingrid sheldon a republican council member who 
describes herself as prochoice but against the provision 
in tuesdays races 
in missouri st louis county which does not include the 
city of st louis votes on a proposed increase in hotel and motel 
taxes kansas city mo voters consider a 189 monthly fee for 
curbside trash recycling 
wisconsin voters choose a judge for a 10year term on the 
supreme court consider a constitutional limit on the governors 
partial veto power and decide the fate of a state lawmaker recalled 
in an indian spearfishing rights dispute 
in oklahoma tulsa voters elect a mayor and nine councilman as 
the city switches from the city commission to city council form of 
government a move approved by voters last year incumbent mayor 
rodger randle a democrat is opposed by state rep frank pitezel 
a republican for mayor 
