<TEXT>
from the newly initiated quest to send people to 
mars to the decadesold search for a cure for cancer the 
governments science programs are a source of technological 
breakthroughs and national pride federal spending on science is 
far from the largest or fastestgrowing part of the budget but it 
is a favorite target for budgetcutters this is the first in a 
series of articles this year that will track the progress of one 
portion of the federal budget science spending 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
when the white houses chief science adviser 
visited the senate budget committee recently he spent much of his 
time responding to a single recurring complaint 
the panels chairman rep james sasser of tennessee said 
costly projects such as the space station 30 billion over several 
years shortchange other researchers and science students in favor 
of a highvisibility highmedia type operation 
the adviser d allan bromley countered that the expensive 
projects will benefit thousands of scientists and make possible 
scientific understanding of the world of our universe 
the dispute was left unresolved but it sums up a growing 
concern in todays era of relentless federal deficits that a 
burgeoning array of bigticket science programs threatens to crowd 
out a much larger number of less expensive but valuable efforts 
as part of his proposed 12 trillion budget for next year 
president bush wants to spend 68 billion on research and 
development or rampd the studies and experimentation that are at 
the core of science 
billions more spread throughout the budget and not totaled 
would be spent for scientific work that has progressed beyond the 
rampd stage such as the space shuttle 
more than 4 billion would be devoted to five science projects 
alone the space station a study of climatic change missions to 
the moon and mars a giant atom smasher called the superconducting 
super collider and a study of human genes 
investment in research and development is a top priority for 
an administration that believes in investing in the future 
bushs budget request said 
but with congressional work on the fiscal 1991 budget just 
beginning sasser and many of his colleagues are questioning 
whether the government can afford longterm costly initiatives that 
threaten to become more expensive each year 
exploring and uncovering the mysteries of the universe stirs 
us all sasser said but i am afraid we are looking at the 
stars right now from a rather deep fiscal hole 
federal spending on science is not large relative to the rest of 
the budget for example the military will take close to 300 
billion this year 
nor are federal science expenditures growing at an alarming 
rate compared to other accounts adjusted for inflation they are 
barely larger than in the late 1960s medicaid spending meanwhile 
is expected to grow by 15 percent to 40 billion this year alone 
but the grammrudman deficitreduction law is forcing congress 
and the white house to find new sources of savings every year 
making science vulnerable 
large parts of the budget such as social security are too 
politically sensitive to be cut dramatically nor can the 176 
billion in this years interest payments on the national debt be 
cut without causing the government to default 
despite pressure to reduce deficits many people argue that the 
united states cant afford to eliminate largescale science 
programs 
supporters make the same arguments that were heard in 1957 after 
the soviets launched their sputnik satellite the united states 
must remain at the forefront of technology and not just for 
economic reasons 
this country had a goal and a dream when we went to the moon 
what this country is looking for now is goals and dreams said 
robert roe dnj chairman of the house science space and 
technology committee 
one thing this country still has is an advantage in its 
science and technology base says frank press president of the 
national academy of sciences from that point of view the total 
investment in science is justifiable 
but others worry about the tradeoffs 
science is an unmet need but its competing against housing 
education the human side of the ledger says house budget 
committee chairman leon panetta dcalif 
still others complain that too many science spending decisions 
are made by politicians interested primarily in jobs and other 
economic rewards for their home districts 
its like everything else people are getting reelected by 
delivering the bacon says former sen william proxmire dwis 
who until 1989 chaired the senate appropriations subcommittee that 
oversees nasa spending 
congressional support for science is widespread and rarely 
breaks down along party lines but to generalize it has stronger 
backing from conservatives than from liberals who from time to 
time try to shift some science spending into social programs 
as with many areas of the budget support for specific projects 
tends to be strongest from those whose congressional committees 
oversee the programs or whose districts will benefit from them 
hence sen phil gramm rtexas one of congress most fervent 
advocates of spending cuts strongly supports the costly super 
collider because it is to be built in his state 
many who question federal support for expensive science programs 
say they soak up money that would be better spent for small 
projects that involve basic science that work often conducted by 
individual researchers involves a search for basic knowledge 
regardless of its potential application 
for example they note that this year for the first time in a 
decade the number of research awards by the national institutes of 
health will fall below 5000 
money also is scarce because of the way the government spends 
its research and development money of the 1990 64 billion total 
only 24 billion will be for civilian projects nearly twothirds 
40 billion will go to military work largely weapons testing 
with little or no application to the rest of the economy 
adding pressure are the peculiarities of the federal budget 
process which pits programs against each other 
the budget committees will make recommendations for spending 
levels that are politically influential but not legally binding 
the appropriations committees make the final decisions 
their subcommittees have jurisdiction over seemingly random 
groupings of programs it is at that level that dollars are 
distributed among competing demands 
rep robert traxler dmich chairs the appropriations 
subcommittee that oversees nasa the national science foundation 
housing veterans and environmental programs 
what am i supposed to do for science he asked take money 
from the homeless 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

