<DOCNO> AP900402-0005 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
jockeying for federal science dollars is 
intensifying as demands increase but the money available remains 
roughly constant 
when inflation is considered the government spends barely more 
for research and development today than it did at the height of the 
apollo moon program in the late 1960s 
adding to the competition is the sheer number of participants 
involved in distribution and pursuit of science funding dozens of 
congressional committees and federal agencies thousands of private 
companies and institutions and an estimated 53 million american 
scientists and engineers 
when world war ii ended the government was spending less than 
1 billion annually on research and development most of it for 
atomic weapons work spending grew slowly until the soviets orbited 
the sputnik satellite in 1957 provoking concern about the 
competitiveness of american science and sparking the growth of the 
us space program 
as a result government science spending grew well into the 
1960s leveling off during the vietnam war dollar amounts 
increased with the energy crisis of the late 1970s and president 
reagans defense buildup of the 1980s but spending adjusted for 
inflation changed little 
president bush is proposing 68 billion in science spending for 
the next fiscal year up about 4 billion from this year 
translated into 1982 dollars to even out the effects of 
inflation the government will spend the equivalent of 482 
billion this year for research and development barely more than 
the 46 billion it spent in 1967 
but nearly twothirds of the spending goes for military 
research mainly on weapons making the competition for civilian 
research and development money even more intense 
again using 1982 dollars the government will spend 181 
billion on civilian research and development in 1990 less than 
the 224 billion spent in 1966 
today 26 house and senate committees are involved in science 
policy and spending ninetysix federal agencies and agency 
subdivisions play a role in research and development according to 
the national science foundation 
but just five agencies spend 95 percent of the money the 
pentagon the department of health and human services the energy 
department the national aeronautics and space administration and 
the national science foundation which distributes grants and keeps 
track of federal science efforts 
in 1988 15 agencies accounted for more than 99 percent of 
federal academic support for science they distributed money to 
2769 universities and colleges 46 offices of academic systems 
such as state university headquarters and 717 nonprofit 
independent institutions such as hospitals 
to conduct its own scientific work ranging from the study of 
aids to development of highspeed trains the government employs 
218000 scientists and engineers according to the science 
foundation 
some work at the more than 700 national laboratories the 
government either operates directly or pays other institutions to 
run on the large end of the scale are the 8400 employees at the 
sandia national laboratories in albuquerque nm and livermore 
calif at the other extreme are the 16 workers at the kodiak 
national laboratory in kodiak alaska where shellfish are studied 
in his proposed 1991 budget president bush is pressing for 
annual installments for a number of major scientific initiatives 
that will take years to complete 
six of the biggest and their projected overall costs are 
a 3 billion effort to map human genes in an effort to treat 
genetic diseases and advance agriculture medicine and other fields 
the 8 billion super collider a circular atomsmasher that 
will measure 54 miles around about to be built in texas it will 
be the worlds most expensive scientific instrument 
the socalled mission to planet earth involving nasa and other 
agencies to study global change at a cost of at least 20 billion 
over 20 years 
the 30 billion space station scheduled for construction in 
the mid1990s 
a return by astronauts to the moon in the 1990s and a manned 
mission to mars early in the next century which nasa says could 
cost 541 billion 
the aerospace plane considered part of the moonmars effort 
but which could be developed independently it would take off and 
land like a conventional airplane yet reach speeds above 4000 mph 
if approved construction of two aircraft would begin in 1993 take 
four to five years and cost more than 5 billion 
</TEXT>
