<TEXT>
they are an unlikely group of backroom 
politicians the rabbi of belz the rabbi of gur and the venerable 
litvak 93yearold rabbi eliezer menachem schach 
israels political system is tangled and these three leaders of 
the haredim ultraorthodox jews have the power to decide who 
will lead the next government 
although israel is a jewish state rabbis seldom emerge as 
political kingmakers outrage has been the most common reaction 
among israelis who are overwhelmingly secular 
thousands of israelis tuned in to a televised speech last week 
by rabbi schach a leader in two ultraorthodox parties 
his factions and agudat israel the third ultrareligious party 
hold a pivotal 13 seats in the 120member parliament they can 
determine whether shimon peres the labor party leader is able to 
form a new coalition 
religious party leaders said for a week that schachs speech 
would be a political bombshell and break the parliamentary tie 
between labor and the rightwing likud bloc of yitzhak shamir 
acting prime minister of a caretaker government 
it was a political dud however more of a sermon in which the 
whitebearded rabbi wearing the black hat of religious jews 
literally wagged his finger and lectured israel for ignoring jewish 
traditions 
many were angered by his criticism of the kibbutzim or 
collective farms which led in the settlement of israel and in 
fighting its wars 
schach accused the kibbutzim of raising nonkosher pigs and 
rabbits and of forgetting traditions that have kept jews together 
for 2000 years if there is a war with what will they fight 
he asked 
much of the resentment stemmed from the fact that many 
ultraorthodox are nonzionist and do not accept the state of 
israel their children often avoid army service studying religion 
into their late 20s or early 30s in yeshivas 
i propose to whomever wants to look at the rabbits in the 
kibbutzim that they also look at the cemeteries and count there how 
many kibbutzniks were killed in the wars said raphael eitan a 
former army chief of staff and rightwing politician 
yossi sarid head of the leftwing citizens rights movement 
said i ask if there is somebody among us who in the next war 
will do without the boys from the kibbutz and instead send the 
yeshiva students 
schach criticized the centerleft labor party for its 
detachment from jewish tradition and included likud its 
conservative rival in all the others that have no link to 
judaism 
the lack of a clear endorsement meant politicians on both sides 
continued wooing the ultraorthodox parties offering political 
jobs and funds for yeshivas as enticements and feeding the anger 
of many israelis 
parliament member yigal bibi of the national religious party 
which is not ultraorthodox described the events as a sad moment 
in the life of israel 
the people have had enough he said its as if weve 
returned to the 18th century the war of the lithuanians and 
the hassidim has gone beyond any limit 
bibi referred to the dispute between the hassidim hebrew for 
pietists who arose in poland and the mitnaggedim or 
opponents who originated in lithuania 
agudat israel is a base for the hassidim who stress the 
emotional side of judaism rabbi simha alter who lives in israel 
but has the title rabbi of gur in the ukraine is one of its 
leaders 
rabbi schach is a litvak or native of lithuania he is of the 
mitnaggedim sect which was formed in reaction to the hassidim and 
emphasizes talmudic scholarship 
in his battle with agudat the rabbi helped create shas and 
degel hatorah the two political groups he represents his chief 
ally in degel hatorah or torah flag is rabbi dov rokeach who has 
the title rabbi of belz in the ukraine 
at the moment the ancient and modern disputes of the 
ultraorthodox keep peres from lining up the 61 parliament votes he 
needs to form a government 
because peres has a tentative promise of agudats five votes he 
is unlikely to get the support of the eight members who represent 
shas and degel hatorah 
the irony of it is that schach would seem labors natural ally 
in his televised speech the rabbi expressed willingness to give 
up the israelioccupied west bank and gaza strip in return for 
peace with the palestinians who live there a view labor shares and 
likud rejects 
one of schachs allies rabbi ovadia yosef brought down 
shamirs government march 15 yosef withdrew his backing from 
shamir when the prime minister refused compromises aimed at 
starting peace talks with palestinians 
