the us government is requiring some french 
and italian vineyards to certify that wines imported by this 
country do not contain traces of a fungicide not approved in the 
united states a spokesman says 
we have found a little bit of italian sparkling wine and some 
french wine that contains traces of a fungicide not approved in the 
united states food and drug administration spokesman bill grigg 
said sunday 
there is no ban on the wines he said but the vineyards 
involved must retain independent testing labs to certify the wines 
are fungicidefree before shipping them to the united states 
the fda will conduct spot tests on the wines to reaffirm the 
certifications said grigg 
the fungicide procymidone is made in japan and is applied to 
grapes while they are growing rather than to the wines themselves 
said grigg 
grigg said only a tiny percentage of total exports from the two 
countries to the united states was affected 
he said there is no indication the fungicide approved for use 
in europe constitutes a health risk but it has not undergone 
us clearance procedures 
