planners of peorias tricentennial 
celebration are going shopping across the river for a little 
history 
the group the peoria 1691 foundation has proposed buying four 
old houses in missouri and moving them to illinois to reconstruct a 
french colony of the banks of the illinois river just like the 
settlement that evolved into peoria 
the original village in what is now downtown peoria was 
destroyed by fire in 1812 so civic leaders have set their sights 
on the french colonial houses built in the late 18th and early 19th 
centuries in ste genevieve mo 
but what might play in peoria doesnt play well in ste 
genevieve 
this is just like the rape of antiquities in the colonial 
days said melburn thurman a ste genevieve anthropologist 
this is a totally unethical and reprehensible action by the city 
of peoria they are trying to steal our great prize our historic 
jewel 
but dorothy sinclair administrative director of the peoria 
historical society views the action as one of historic 
preservation 
we came along and expressed an interest in them after learning 
they were being sold and threatened with possible destruction 
mrs sinclair said 
we did not go down there in the night and carry them away we 
think its better they be saved and preserved in peoria than being 
torn down in ste genevieve 
ste genevieve a town of 5000 situated 75 miles south of st 
louis was once part of frances louisiana territory bought by the 
united states in 1803 
the historical society estimates it would cost 500000 to buy 
and relocate the houses the nonprofit group would raise the money 
through donations and doesnt need peoria officials approval 
ste genevieve city commissioners could block the plan since the 
houses are on the national registry of historic places but they 
have taken no action so far the peoria group has yet to sign an 
agreement to buy the houses 
royce and margaret wilhauk who own three of the houses said 
they contacted the state of missouri after officials in peoria made 
an offer last fall 
we have given the state an option on the houses and theyve 
asked for an extension mrs wilhauk said wed like the houses 
to stay here but if we cant work something out we will consider 
the peoria offer 
frank myers of ste genevieves foundation for preservation says 
the houses should stay wed like to share our knowledge with 
peoria but we dont necessarily want to share our buildings with 
peoria he said 
