<TEXT>
the united states has told afghan 
guerrillas to stay out of the drug business or risk losing support 
in the fight against their countrys government a senior american 
official said today 
what we have made very clear to the mujahedeen commanders is 
that they must stay out of drugs and that they must discourage 
production of drugs said melvyn levitsky an asssistant 
secretary of state for international narcotics matters 
we cannot accept a situation where we are giving assistance to 
the mujahedeen and they on the other hand are encouraging drug 
production and drug trafficking he said at the end of a 
threeday visit to pakistan 
the major mujahedeen groups which are based in pakistan have 
acknowledged that some of their local commanders are involved in 
poppy cultivation but the groups leaders deny they condone it 
levitsky is touring thailand india pakistan and turkey as part 
of president bushs efforts to involve more countries in the fight 
against drugs 
afghanistan produced an estimated 750 tons of opium in 1988 
making it the worlds second biggest supplier after burma 
the decadeold war between the sovietbacked government in kabul 
and the moslem guerrillas has destroyed much of afghanistans 
agrarian economy 
but the fighting has turned the small centuriesold tradition of 
poppy cultivation into a multimillion dollar industry and spawned 
what many pakistanis call the heroin and kalashnikov culture 
referring to the preferred automatic weapon of the regions drug 
lords 
the poppies yield a sticky substance that is refined into heroin 
powder in makeshift laboratories along the rugged frontier and then 
spirited through pakistan to markets in europe and the united 
states 
the united states provides an estimated 300 million in annual 
assistance to the mujahedeen or holy warriors who are fighting to 
replace the communiststyle government in kabul 
levitsky said washington would not support any government in 
afghanistan that tolerated or encouraged drug production and 
trafficking 
the point we have made to the mujahedeen is that if there is 
considerable evidence that there is support for drug production 
and drug trafficking we would not be able to assistant that 
government he said 
opium production and to some extent export have existed for 
centuries in afghanistan and pakistan 
poppy cultivation has declined steadily in pakistan but it has 
risen sharply in afghanistan where tribal areas along the 
mountainous frontier have become a haven for drug lords 
the united states has only recently started working with 
guerrilla leaders to discourage poppy cultivation and launched a 
program to promote drug awareness among the insurgents offering 
incentives to substitute poppy with other crops but most are 
unattractive to poppy growers accustomed to huge profits 
according to us officials about 80 percent of the heroin sold 
in europe and 25 percent sold in the united states comes from 
afghanistan pakistan and iran the socalled golden crescent 
the rest comes from mexico and the golden triangle of thailand 
laos and burma 
we are now beginning to look very seriously at a 
counterheroin strategy levitsky told a news conference 
many experts believe that the crackcocaine epidemic may not 
last so long based on the history of epidemics centered on 
stimulants like cocaine being rather shortlived and often being 
followed by an epidemic based on depressants like heroin he said 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

