<TEXT>
japans whaling fleet returned from the antarctic 
ocean after catching 330 small whales in the third season of a 
controversial research program aimed at counting the whale 
population officials said today 
we believe we were able to achieve good scientific results 
from the research said nobuyuki yagi a fishery agency official 
after the expedition ended saturday 
the japanese government hopes the international whaling 
commission which imposed a worldwide moratorium on commercial 
whaling in 1986 will decide there are sufficient numbers of some 
species to partially lift the ban 
japanese whaling officials say the mammals must be killed to 
accurately determine their age sex diet and health but 
antiwhaling groups call the research a veiled form of commercial 
whaling and say skin sampling and other nonlethal research methods 
are available 
good weather and frequent sightings allowed japans fourship 
whaling fleet to catch 30 more nonendangered minke whales than its 
original 300whale quota during the fourmonth expedition yagi 
said 
the research whaling plan allows a 10 percent leeway in the 
catch he said 
yagi said japan will present its findings on numbers sex and 
age to the international whaling commission which currently 
estimates there are about 730000 minkes 
the commissions moratorium on whaling was passed to allow 
scientists to study whale stocks without the disruptions caused by 
regular whaling activities 
the commissions scientific commission is to meet in june to 
recommend whether to extend the moratorium followed by a decision 
by the full commission at a meeting scheduled in july 
even if the scientific committee agrees after studying the 
scientific findings that commercial whaling should be resumed 
there is a large possibility that the full commission will reject 
it because of opposition within it to whaling yagi said 
many of the 38 nations in the commission do not conduct whaling 
and several are strong whaling opponents under the commissions 
charter members are allowed to conduct research whaling whenever 
they wish despite the commercial whaling ban 
environmental groups have charged that japans research program 
is actually commercial whaling in disguise 
the same boats and facilities are used as in commercial whaling 
and the meat obtained by the research program is sold for food as 
permitted under the commissions regulations 
japan halted commercial whaling in the antarctic at the end of 
the 198687 season when it caught 1941 whales it then began a 
program of research whaling which it says is aimed at assessing 
whale stocks 
japanese whalers killed 273 minke whales in the first year of 
the program and 241 last year 
japanese whaling officials have said at least 825 whales must be 
caught each year to make the research program scientifically 
accurate the quota for the programs first year was initially 875 
but strong opposition from environmental groups and from other 
commission members led japan to reduce the quota to 300 
in the early 1960s when japanese whaling was at its peak 
whales provided about 23 percent of all meat consumed in the 
country since then declining whale supplies have turned it into a 
delicacy 
