<TEXT>
the european community today submitted a detailed 
proposal to trade negotiators for new international rules to 
protect rights to intellectual property such as patents copyright 
and trademarks 
the proposal is the most comprehensive presented to date in the 
general agreement on tariffs and trade talks and aims to combat 
increasing counterfeiting and piracy 
the ecs draft to be discussed by negotiators at gatts 
headquarters in geneva would protect patents for 20 years to 
prevent third parties from making using or selling a product 
without the patent owners consent 
copyrighting including the rights of authors performers and 
broadcast organizations is protected for 25 to 50 years and the 
initial registration of a trademark would be valid for 10 years 
under the proposal 
new accords on intellectual property rights and 14 other sectors 
of world trade are due to be signed by gatts 96 members in 
december at the end of a fouryear round of negotiations 
while the socalled uruguay round talks on areas such as 
agriculture and textiles are designed to liberalize global 
commerce any agreement on intellectual property is likely to 
increase protection 
the united states the 12nation european bloc and japan have 
pressed for more stringent gatt rules the united states is 
expected to submit a similarly detailed proposal on intellectual 
property in the next few weeks 
by contrast some developing countries led by india have argued 
that ready access to knowhow is essential to their development and 
that it should not be controlled through gatt 
peter carl mogens an ec negotiator said even though 
conventions already existed in these areas basic rights were not 
observed 
he said the plans for new rules on trademarks were meant to 
prevent the sale of counterfeit goods which not only harmed 
producers of the genuine product but but often posed a health risk 
as in the case of counterfeit medicines 
a few internationally agreed rules protect patents mogens said 
but some countries notably india refused to respect patents for 
medicines 
the ec draft also sets out protective measures for geographical 
indications or appelations of origin where the quality and 
reputation of a product is linked with a country or region 
mogens said many countries did not respect an existing 
international treaty citing the example of a third world country 
that imposed an import ban on french champagne while continuing to 
sell a homeproduced version bearing the same name he did not name 
the country 
other areas covered in the ecs proposal are the design of 
semiconductors trade secrets and industrial designs 
