the federal government has paid about 23 million 
since 1979 for legal fees of rocky flats nuclear weapons plant 
operators who were sued on behalf of workers allegedly killed or 
injured by radiation a newspaper reported today 
yet total damages sought by seven widows and one living worker 
whose cases have come to trial is only about 1 million the denver 
post said 
the post quoted federal records which show the governments 
share of that potential liability is less than 400000 the rest 
of the claims would have been paid out of a state fund created by 
colorado employers 
to date two widows have won workers compensation lawsuits 
collecting a total of about 60000 a third case has been settled 
out of court for an estimated 10000 
in each case the government has argued that the workers deaths 
and cancers were caused by something other than exposure to 
onthejob radiation 
the inspector general of the department of energy which owns 
the rocky flats plant outside denver will conduct an informal 
review to determine if the legal fees are justified said rob 
jacques an assistant to the inspector general 
the legal fee records obtained by the denver post through the 
freedom of information act show that the money was paid by the 
plants two previous operators dow chemical and rockwell 
international corp to the denver law firm of martinez amp allman 
the department of energy then reimbursed the plant operators 
attorneys robert allman and larry martinez said the key legal 
decisions in each case were made by their clients the plant 
operators and the energy department 
federal records show the two lawyers billed an average of nearly 
30000 a month from june 1984 through january 1990 even though 
most of the official legal appearances hearings and appeals were 
concluded before june 1984 
during 1986 and 1987 state records show almost no formal legal 
proceedings took place on any of the cases yet the lawyers charged 
the government 341000 and 273000 for each year respectively 
between 1979 and june 1984 the government spent roughly 
425000 defending its operators the records show since then the 
government has paid almost 19 million on legal fees 
according to bruce deboskey the denver lawyer who has 
represented each of the widows and workers filing cases against 
rocky flats martinez and allman routinely turned down offers to 
settle cases for less than what was being claimed and only settled 
one case in which a living rocky flats worker was the claimant 
this appears to be the last vestige of an official government 
policy to defeat the claims of the widows of rocky flats workers 
regardless of the cost or the consequences to the taxpayers or to 
the workers compensation system deboskey said 
