the commissioners recessed their meeting indefinitely after 
gorski announced that an aide to gov mario cuomo indicated some 
state aid might be available to get the transit system running 
commissioners said they wanted to know more about that possibility 
in albany cuomo spokeswoman anne crowley said she knew nothing 
about the possibility of the state stepping in 
teachers threatened a court fight on behalf of high school 
students who use the mass transit system 
the shutdown of the system deprives 11000 buffalo high school 
students of transportation said philip rumore president of the 
buffalo teachers federation 
the union said sunday it would try to force the transit 
authority back into business by going to federal court and claiming 
the shutdown cripples a courtordered school desegregation program 
begun in 1976 
public and private schools in new yorks secondlargest city 
were open today and buffalos 25000 elementary students rode 
privately contracted buses as usual 
rumore said attendance in buffalo high schools was 50 percent of 
normal 
motorists didnt face bigcity style gridlock buffalo with a 
population of about 324000 doesnt have that type of traffic 
but people can expect at least a halfhour delay coming into the 
city parking board director thomas gallagher said 
the evening commute could be worse with road work closing or 
restricting lanes on three major roads out of downtown 
gallagher said about 65 percent of the 55000 to 58000 people 
who work downtown commute by car and there are about 24000 parking 
spaces downtown 
if most of the people who use public transportation dont stay 
home we couldnt handle everybody coming in gallagher said 
one woman tennizee high said she walked an hour and a half to 
get to her downtown job everybody was walking together with 
sneakers on she said can you believe it 
cathy wlodarczyk manager of a burger king said all her 
employees got to work this morning we had it planned ahead of 
time who was supposed to pick up whom most of them walked she 
said 
