<TEXT>
ssociated press writerpluswashington ap the jury in john m 
poindexters trial began deliberating today whether the former 
national security adviser was guilty of withholding details of the 
irancontra affair from congress 
us district judge harold greene instructed the jury of eight 
women and four men to ignore the merits of president reagans 
policies of helping the nicaraguan rebels or selling arms to iran 
in an attempt to free american hostages 
its not for you to decide who was right in political disputes 
between congress and the president between democrats and 
republicans or between liberals and conservatives greene told 
the jury 
you are not called on to decide if the presidents policy 
toward iran and the american hostages was a wise or unwise 
policy the judge said he told them instead to focus on any 
evidence of particular crimes as distinct from broad policy 
poindexter who was reagans national security adviser from late 
1985 to november 1986 is accused of conspiring with former white 
house aide oliver l north and others to obstruct congressional 
inquiries about covert assistance given the contras and usiran 
arms sales 
he also faces charges of obstructing congress and making false 
statements to lawmakers 
in final arguments on friday defense lawyer richard beckler 
told jurors that poindexter a retired navy rear admiral was not 
part of some grimy little conspiracy that the prosecution would 
have you believe 
he tried to suggest that north went behind poindexters back 
saying there was absolutely many things that admiral poindexter 
didnt know oliver north was doing 
beckler told jurors that irancontra prosecutors produced as a 
witness only one of poindexters alleged coconspirators fawn 
hall and that the former white house secretary testified she only 
had a nodding acquaintance with the retired navy rear admiral 
but greene told jurors it was not necessary for prosecutors to 
prove that all the conspirators knew each other or that poindexter 
knew everything that other members of the alleged conspiracy were 
doing 
prosecutors must show that the defendant knew or had reason to 
know a conspiracy existed and actions were being taken to further 
its goals the judge said 
according to testimony by north and hall who was his secretary 
the two destroyed numerous irancontra documents as the diversion 
of usiran armssale profits to the contras was uncovered by 
investigators 
prosecutor dan webb said poindexter contributed to this 
rampage of destruction by deleting 5000 electronic messages in 
his office computer that contained a wealth of information about 
the irancontra affair 
investigators recovered the documents from a computer backup 
system 
poindexter met with north after he discovered that justice 
department investigators were coming over to the white house to 
look for documents during the weekend of nov 2123 1986 
according to testimony 
the prosecution contends that ms hall who was given immunity 
was part of the conspiracy because she helped north destroy or 
remove secret documents 
other alleged coconspirators who did not testify included 
poindexters predecessor as national security advisor robert 
mcfarlane and retired air force maj gen richard v secord both 
have pleaded guilty to irancontra charges and are cooperating with 
irancontra prosecutors 
beckler chided the prosecution for pinning the blame on 
poindexter for the efforts of the missing bud mcfarlane to 
mislead congress in 1985 about covert efforts to assist the 
nicaraguan contra rebels 
mcfarlane pleaded guilty to misdemeanor charges of withholding 
information from congress while north was convicted last year of 
aiding and abetting an obstruction of a congressional inquiry 
secord pleaded guilty to making a false statement to congress 
