<TEXT>
chancellor helmut kohl tried to 
placate angry east germans on monday after the head of bonns 
central bank suggested swapping east german marks 2to1 for west 
german marks 
postal workers in the east german city of suhl held a warning 
strike monday to press for a 1to1 exchange rate east germanys 
labor union federation urged a nationwide demonstration thursday 
east germans were expecting to get a powerful west german mark 
for each of their east german marks under a common currency 
expected to be worked out sometime this summer 
karl otto poehl the influential head of west germanys central 
bank the bundesbank suggested the 2to1 conversion rate 
the suggestion raised allegations kohl was breaking campaign 
promises made before the march 18 east german elections an 
alliance favoring quick reunification won the vote in part because 
of campaigning by kohl 
both german states have agreed to set up a common currency as a 
crucial step toward unification with west germany eventually 
taking over east germanys economic policies bonn would like the 
currency union in place by july 1 
kohl said monday his government will carefully examine the 
bundesbanks recommendation and insisted no decision had been 
made on what exchange rate to use 
the chancellor said he recognizes his responsibility to the 
people of east germany saying i have repeatedly underlined 
this commitment to solidarity during the east german election 
campaign and i stand by it 
during the campaign kohl promised that east german private 
savings would not be decimated by monetary union he said east 
germans would be protected from economic shocks when the currency 
union takes effect 
but the bundesbank repeated its demand that east german marks be 
exchanged 2to1 with the exception of a 1to1 conversion for 
personal savings of up to 2000 eastern marks 
a conversion rate of 1to1 would expose the east german 
economy to an indebtedness and a cost level with which most 
companies couldnt cope in international competition the 
bundesbank said in a statement 
financial experts have previously cautioned that many east 
german factories and shops would not be able to afford wages and 
pensions if east german marks were traded for western marks at 
parity there have been forecasts up to 2 million east germans 
could lose their jobs 
the bundesbank controls the west german money supply it has 
demanded full control of east german monetary policy when currency 
union occurs 
the bundesbank also wants limits on new borrowings by the east 
german public sector 
there were clear signs of tension between kohls government and 
the bundesbank over the issue of conversion rates 
helmut haussmann west germanys economics minister said a 
decision on conversion rates will be made by the government and not 
by the bank 
the bundesbank has made a recommendation the decision will be 
made by politics he told the masscirculation bild newspaper 
foreign minister hansdietrich genscher said the bundesbanks 
recommendations do not mark the last word on a conversion rate 
genscher said that for east german pensions especially a more 
favorable rate must be considered than 2to1 
that is not acceptable how could anyone be expected to live 
with such a pension genscher said in an interview with 
deutschlandfunk radio 
lothar de maiziere east germanys premierdesignate warned the 
east german exodus to west germany could swell again if his 
countrymen sense monetary union could do them more harm than good 
in that case we would be able to keep the people here only 
with great difficulties said de maiziere 
