<TEXT>
the number of political prisoners in soviet mental 
institutions may have declined sharply but the abuse of 
psychiatric practices remains widespread an international group 
said monday 
the abuses continue and the abusers are still in place the 
international association on the political use of psychiatry said 
in a statement 
robert van voren the general secretary of the netherlands 
group said the situation in the soviet union remains a cause of 
concern 
van voren who recently visited the soviet union said 
affiliated groups in that nation have files on 40 political 
prisoners kept in psychiatric hospitals that compares with about 
1000 five years ago 
he said it was not possible to estimate the total number of 
political prisoners under psychiatric care because many patients 
were being shifted to remote areas 
it is clear that authorities are still trying to cover up 
abuses he said 
van voren said the soviet interior ministry still maintains 
control over what he estimated to be more than 1000 psychiatric 
hospitals throughout the country 
there are still watchtowers with machine guns still guards 
with dogs still barbed wire and doctors are still holding 
military ranks at those hospitals he said 
van voren said the situation in most of the hospitals has not 
improved since mikhail s gorbachev came to power in 1985 recently 
instituted legal changes give only theoretical rights to 
patients van voren said 
he hailed the formation of independent psychiatric associations 
in moscow leningrad and estonia and said there were very strong 
attempts by lawyers and activists to reform soviet psychiatry 
van voren said the soviet media have been writing openly about 
current abuses including a case in which a declared candidate in a 
local election was taken to a psychiatric hospital on orders from 
the opposing communist party candidate 
but he said the leadership of the official soviet allunion 
society for psychiatry has remained in power despite promises from 
the organization for changes when it was readmitted to the world 
psychiatric association in october 
van vorens group opposed that readmission and said monday it 
would be a good thing to reconsider that membership 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

