an 81yearold woman left nearly her 
entire 600000 estate to make sure a pet pig and her dog are taken 
care of for the rest of their lives 
neighbors said margo lamp loved animals and was especially fond 
of her german shepherd named calamity jane cammy for short and 
a runt hog called mr pig the pig followed her around the yard on 
the porch and sometimes in the house 
there was certainly no question about the pig being a pet 
said george goebel attorney for ms lamps estate he would come 
up and rub against your pant leg and she fed him cat food 
about 100 less social pigs on the farm have been sold since her 
death six weeks ago 
ms lamp left bequests of 1000 each to friends in colorado and 
germany but left the rest to her animals 
ms lamp said in her will that the pets should be taken care of 
with the profits from her farm near davenport in eastern iowa and 
other assets the estate goes to the scott county humane society 
after the needs of the pets are met 
neighbors said ms lamp lived a solitary life but kept abreast 
of world events by subscribing to four newspapers and traveling to 
new york once a year to visit art museums 
she used to say she believed in solitude and that there was a 
difference between solitude and loneliness said a neighbor jack 
armstrong 
the farm was first run by ms lamps father hugo lamp it was 
one of the first in the area to have a combine 
ms lamp who never married lived alone on the 320acre farm 
she lost interest in the place when a hired man died in 1975 and 
allowed the buildings to become run down 
louis nielsen president of the scott county humane society 
said the society will collect rent on the farm while mr pig and 
cammy are alive after that the society may do as it wishes with 
the farm 
 
