us and japanese negotiators reached 
agreement on a oneyear pact to triple the number of observers on 
japanese driftnet boats and equip all the vessels with monitoring 
transmitters the state department said monday 
critics however said the pact would provide observers for only 
10 percent of japans driftnet vessels and allow the japanese to 
continue to fish the cold salmonrich waters south of the aleutian 
islands 
we still fall short of our goal of eliminating highseas drift 
nets but this is quite an improvement over last years 
agreement said sen ted stevens ralaska 
a spokesman for the state departments office of oceans 
environment and science tom snead said department negotiator ed 
wolfe had reached the agreement over the weekend in japan 
the pact calls for 98 vessels from japans squid and largemesh 
driftnet fleets to be monitored in the 1990 fishing season by 47 
us 41 japanese and 10 canadian observers last year 32 japanese 
driftnet vessels were covered by observers 
now we dont have to play hideandseek with the japanese 
rep john miller rwash said 
the us has made a step in the right direction but its not 
the final answer massive driftnetting efforts need to be 
eliminated drift nets take too many fish and kill too many marine 
mammals and sea birds he said 
the monitoring transmitters will send signals to satellites 
enabling the government to tell when the vessels enter waters where 
driftnetting is illegal critics of driftnetting say the 
mileslong nets illegally capture north americaspawned salmon and 
kill thousands of marine birds and mammals 
