<DOCNO> AP900402-0146 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
republican party chairman lee atwater entered 
a new york hospital monday for intense radiation treatment of a 
type of brain tumor that experts say is persistent and dangerous 
mary matalin chief of staff for the republican national 
committee said in a statement that doctors had determined atwater 
has an astrocytoma a type of tumor that has the potential to 
behave aggressively 
the tumor was diagnosed last month after atwater collapsed 
during a speech 
dr stuart grossman director of neurological onocology at the 
johns hopkins oncology center in baltimore said astrocytomas are 
tough tumors to cure they do have a tendency to come back 
astrocytomas are graded i through iv although grade iv is 
usually called by another name the announcement did not identify 
the grade of atwaters tumor 
all of these types of tumors are potentially curable and 
potentially fatal said dr r william harter an associate 
professor of radiation onocology at georgetown unversity hospital 
he said for a grade i astrocytoma the fiveyear survival rate is 
about 50 percent when treated aggressively for grade ii he said 
the fiveyear survival rate is 25 percent and for grade iii it is 
10 percent to 20 percent 
grade iv more commonly called glioblastoma multiforme or 
anaplastic astrocytoma are always fatal harter said 
grossman cautioned that a five year survival does not equal 
cure 
these types of tumors usually come back he said 
another physician who spoke on condition of anonymity said 
patients with astrocytomas run a substantial risk of dying from 
this disease at some point 
one source familiar with the case said doctors found cells 
within the tumor that had the potential for sudden growth the 
source who also spoke on condition of anonymity said there had 
been no growth in the tumor diagnosed march 6 
atwater 39 checked into new york citys montefiore medical 
center where doctors planned to insert radioactive isotopes into 
the tumor on the right side of his brain after the procedure done 
under local anesthesia the isotopes remain implanted for five days 
the treatment is under the direction of dr paul l kornblith 
chairman of neurological surgery at the albert einstein college of 
medicine 
mr atwaters age and excellent physical condition together 
with the early diagnosis of the tumor its size and location offer 
favorable circumstances for successful results kornblith said 
the treatment provides a higher dose of radiation targeted on 
the tumor over a shorter time period matalin said 
the rnc announcement said atwaters tumor is in the frontal 
lobe both harter and grossman said the frontal lobe is more easily 
treated without the risk of loss of function than are most other 
areas of the brain 
harter said patients receiving radioactive isotope treatment 
directly on brain tumors seldom suffer acute side effects and most 
are able to work while the treatment is under way 
every two to three months after receiving such therapy patients 
are reexamined with xray or magnetic images taken to determine 
if the tumor is growing 
you can have a problem on down the line in that the area 
exposed to the radiation may shrivel up grossman said the 
brain doesnt handle such dead tissue very well so you have to go 
in and clear it of dead cells 
in cincinnati president bush said he wished atwater his best 
right now theres nothing more important for lee to do than 
get well and i know thats exactly what he intends to do given 
that fighting spirit bush said while campaigning for george 
voinovich the gop gubernatorial candidate in ohio 
after atwater was first hospitalized doctors said the tumor was 
nonmalignant and would be treated with daily radiation therapy 
over a fiveweek period 
the doctors are sticking by the original thing that its 
small and its very treatable said charles black a political 
consultant who is a close friend and former business partner of 
