<TEXT>
the commerce department moved on monday to 
free exports of harddisk drives for personal computers 
last year us sales to other countries were worth about 500 
million the department said despite licensing requirements 
imposed to keep them out of the soviet union and its allies 
dropping the curbs is expected to lead to a large increase in sales 
on wednesday the licensing restrictions will be removed for 
sales of disks with a capacity of 45 megabytes to almost all 
countries outside the soviet union and its allies one megabyte 
holds roughly a million characters 
the net result of this decontrol will be to focus and maintain 
export restrictions on those items that are truly strategic and can 
be controlled effectively said dennis e kloske undersecretary 
of commerce for export control in a statement 
the department has decided the harddisk drives can be bought 
freely from other countries so there is no reason to prevent 
american companies from competing for the business 
for sales to the soviets and its east european allies the 
commerce department is submitting a proposal to the coordinating 
committee on multilateral export controls cocom in paris this 
group includes the member countries of nato except for iceland 
plus japan and australia 
until cocom rules the commerce department will continue to 
require export licenses for shipments to eastern europe countries 
it said 
if cocom agrees as it is expected to do within a few months 
us disk drives will be available for sale anywhere in the world 
except to libya cuba vietnam north korea cambodia and the 
police and armed forces of south africa 
