traces of a fungicide not approved in the 
united states have been found in 11 samples of imported wines the 
food and drug administration said monday 
there is no ban on the wines and none is being recalled said 
fda spokesman bill grigg but the fda is requiring the makers of 
these wines to certify that they do not contain the fungicide 
procymidone before they are shipped to this country 
grigg said the vineyards involved must retain independent 
testing labs to certify that the wines are fungicidefree before 
shipping them to the united states he said the fda will conduct 
spot tests on the wines to confirm the certifications 
the maker of procymidone sumitomo chemical co of osaka japan 
has begun providing the environmental protection agency with data 
on the fungicide which is approved in europe the fda said 
this could lead to the setting of a residue tolerance by epa 
currently the epa has no tolerance levels for procymidone which 
means that no amount of it can appear in any products sold here 
grigg said 
he also said there is no indication the fungicide which is 
applied to grapes while they are growing constitutes a health risk 
the fda initiated a 200sample survey after traces of 
procymidone were found in an italian sparkling wine tosti asti 
spumante 
of the 116 wine samples tested so far seven french and three 
italian wines were found to contain traces of the fungicide 
no traces were found in samples of wines from australia brazil 
