<TEXT>
a summary of developments in the news industry for the week of 
march 26april 2 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
the newspaper industrys reluctance to 
embrace videotex threatens to create a vacuum that telephone 
companies and others eventually will fill a top newspaper 
executive said march 26 
we ought to be asking ourselves if we are not in the local 
information business instead of the newspaper business said 
phillip j meek president of the publishing division of capital 
citiesabc inc and former publisher of the fort worth 
startelegram 
speaking at the annual meeting of the texas daily newspaper 
association meek chided the industry for failing to pursue 
videotex computerdelivered information 
he said the failure could leave the market open for telephone 
companies and other competitors 
the newspaper industry has fought efforts by american telephone 
amp telegraph co and some regional phone companies to provide 
information over existing lines but meek said he is frustrated 
and alarmed that nothing is happening within the industry to fill 
the void 
although currently restricted sooner or later if newspapers 
dont do something the phone companies ought to come in meek 
said 
some large newspaper chains have offered videotex services with 
little success and some experts doubt videotex will develop a 
following among the general public 
meek said those past failures have scared off other newspaper 
ventures 
its a narrow audience but its a decent business said 
meek who oversaw the creation of startext a videotex service of 
the fort worth newspaper 
meek said startext begun in 1982 now has about 4200 
subscribers in the dallasfort worth area more than prodigy a 
similar venture of ibm and sears roebuck and co 
newspapers must also be aware of attempts to slice up their 
traditional markets he said pointing to the proliferation of free 
publications that advertise homes jobs cars and other items that 
normally make up a newspapers classified ad section 
suggesting the industry provide some of those publications he 
said if it makes sense its going to happen 
meek also called on the executives to fight proposed changes in 
us postal service regulations that would reduce the mailing costs 
of saturation publications while raising fees for newspapers by 
20 per thousand 
its an unfair break to one segment of direct mail that just 
puts pressures on newspapers he said 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
a suburban kansas city publisher said 
march 29 he plans to launch an afternoon tabloid newspaper designed 
to appeal to news addicts in the wake of the shutdown of the 
afternoon kansas city star 
stephen f rose president and copublisher of sun publications 
inc said the evening news will be published monday through friday 
beginning may 14 
the paper will cost 50 cents and focus on national and 
international news provided by the associated press business news 
and national and local sports 
it will be sold at newsstands convenience stores and newspaper 
racks throughout the metropolitan area but wont be distributed to 
homes which rose said would boost expenses and require earlier 
news deadlines 
we expect it to appeal to busy people who want more 
information people who dont want to wait 24 hours to find out 
what happened today rose said 
on march 1 the kansas city star co stopped publishing the 
afternoon star merged it with the morning times and began 
publishing a sevenday morning newspaper called the kansas city 
star 
we certainly felt it left a vacuum rose said 
joe mcguff editor of the star said he didnt know enough 
details to comment 
well just have to wait and see if a paper of that type will 
work in the afternoon mcguff said 
rose said he would begin publishing 25000 copies a day 
we dont think thats an unreasonable hope but we dont have 
to sell 25000 papers for this to be viable depending on the 
advertising he said 
rose 42 the sole investor declined to provide financial 
details but said hes saving some money by using sun publications 
printing press other equipment and some employees 
sun publications owned by roses family currently publishes 18 
twiceweekly papers in suburban kansas city plus two weeklies 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
media and entertainment giant time warner inc 
said march 27 it has agreed to buy lane publishing co and certain 
related assets for 225 million in cash and stock 
the familyowned lane of menlo park calif publishes sunset 
the magazine of western living and owns sunset books and sunset 
films 
the purchase would be the first major acquisition for time 
warner since time inc completed its 14 billion acquisition of 
warner communications inc in january 
under an agreement in principle time warner said it would pay 
80 million in cash and 145 million in preferred stock for lane 
the purchase would give time warner a second major regional 
publishing operation to complement its southern progress corp 
which publishes southern living and several other magazines 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
diners at more than 60 new york restaurants are 
getting more than a menu when they stop in for a meal 
a new venture owned by a specialty publishing concern and a 
company that owns restaurants is stapling the menus inside a new 
general interest magazine called knife amp fork 
the magazine given to all customers is being billed as a means 
of reaching young affluent consumers who spend little time watching 
television if it is successful in new york its owners say they 
may expand it nationally 
knife amp fork is a creation of a 5050 joint venture by the 
publishing company performance network inc of lindenhurst ny 
and the riese organization a privately held company that owns more 
than 300 restaurants in the new york area and has investment stakes 
in more than 100 others nationwide 
 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
geneva college closed its student 
newspaper march 26 for the rest of the semester after it published 
an editorial critical of roman catholics 
geneva is affiliated with the reformed presbyterian church 
though catholics comprise the largest religious group on campus 
the decision came as the result of a firestorm of complaints 
about editor eric dugans editorial said college spokesman william 
gibbs 
the editorial in the cabinet titled theology of the pointy 
hats says senior clerics in the catholic church who were 
referred to as pointy hats have become authoritarian and 
their councils and traditions supersede scripture 
the editorial says protestants use the bible to assess the 
validity of their leaders statements 
the catholic however finds most of his faith and practice 
moored in the sayings of popes and councils which frequently 
contradict each other the editorial says and just what if one 
pope isnt exactly holy his words are still law 
the editorial closes he who holds to teachings which 
contradict the bible finds a final resting place with the serpent 
gibbs said the decision to close the paper wasnt censorship but 
was an apology to genevas students particularly catholics who 
account for about onefifth of the 1200 students 
dugan said the board acted out of fear the college would lose 
students and tuition 
the college has responded in the way it has in my opinion 
not because of its theological persuasion but because of the 
wealth of their pocketbooks he said 
</TEXT>
