<TEXT>
western journalists covering lithuanias standoff 
with moscow from the baltic republics capital were ordered to 
leave the country and most if not all were out by april 1 
more than 100 journalists based in moscow and other european 
capitals followed events from vilnius before they were ordered to 
leave 
despite the greater freedom of movement permitted under 
glasnost soviet authorities have routinely closed areas stricken 
by ethnic violence to foreign journalists some regions regarded as 
strategically or politically sensitive are closed at all times 
others only temporarily 
the order restricting journalists access to lithuania came as 
the kremlin increased pressure on the rebellious republic and as 
lithuanian leaders sought to use the western media to protect them 
from a use of force to crush their effort to establish an 
independent state 
moscowbased foreign journalists must give the soviet foreign 
ministry advance notice of any plans to travel outside the soviet 
capital including the dates and means of their travel and where 
they will stay outside moscow 
the soviet government may refuse to permit the trip temporarily 
closing areas to foreigners the foreign ministry on march 23 
stopped permitting most moscowbased reporters from traveling to 
lithuania and ordered a number of diplomats out of the republic 
</TEXT>
