masking request by not describing problems she had at one of 
her previous jobs 
the woman knows only two people who identified her from the 
article and they had been therapists for her the judge said the 
article portrayed the woman as someone who successfully recovered 
from an exploitative situation maclaughlin wrote 
to enforce reportersource agreements in litigation plaintiffs 
at a minimum must prove specific unambiguous terms and to 
provide clear and convincing proof that the agreement was 
breached the judge wrote 
the court has no doubt that in balancing the rights of the 
free press with common contractual rights the free press rights 
under the first amendment must be given preference the decision 
said 
elliot rothenberg of minneapolis the womans attorney said he 
is discussing with his client the possibility of an appeal 
if an appeal is filed rothenberg said he would almost certainly 
again invoke the case of dan cohen a twin cities public relations 
agent who received a 700000 jury award in a breach of contract 
lawsuit against the star tribune and st paul pioneer press 
dispatch 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
a divided indiana supreme court in a case 
watched closely by media groups across the nation ruled march 27 
that two newspaper reporters cant be held in contempt of court for 
questioning former members of a grand jury 
in a 32 decision the court threw out earlier state court of 
appeals decisions that said reporter mark kiesling of the times of 
hammond and william heltzel formerly a reporter at the paper 
could be held in contempt because they violated the secrecy of the 
grand jury system 
the contempt citations were sought by former lake county 
prosecutor jack f crawford after the times published stories in 
1987 detailing why a grand jury impaneled in 1984 didnt return 
indictments in an investigation of a township trustees office in 
that county 
a lake county court had thrown out the contempt request before 
the court of appeals in two 1989 decisions ruled that the secrecy 
of the grand jury was of paramount importance and the reporters 
could be punished for inducing jurors to violate hat secrecy 
the threejustice majority of the supreme court held that while 
the reporters actions werent protected by the freedom of the 
press guarantee in the first amendment they didnt rise to the 
level of contempt because the questioning of the jurors occurred 
long after the jury had been dismissed 
the court said the need to protect the secrecy of the grand jury 
is at its peak while the grand jury is in the process of hearing 
testimony deliberating and voting once the proceedings are over 
and the grand jurors have been discharged however the need to 
protect these policies falls off dramatically 
the court took note of a recent us supreme court decision 
striking down a florida law permanently barring grand jury 
witnesses from talking about their testimony however the indiana 
justices said that because their decision was focused narrowly on 
the issue of contempt they didnt have to address the larger issue 
of permanent bans on disclosure of grand jury information 
were absolutely delighted said jan m carroll who filed a 
friendofthe court brief on behalf of a group of media 
organizations including the american society of newspaper editors 
and the society of professional journalists 
this case had farreaching effects not only for reporters but 
for any citizen who had the temerity to ask questions about a grand 
jury said carroll 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

