<TEXT>
ilona nagy is all for democracy but it 
doesnt solve the problem of how to pay a 74 electricity bill and 
still keep a family of six going on the rest of 300 a month 
the monthly budget would be much smaller if she did not have a 
second job her husband daniel has left a secure government 
position to form a private partnership so his income is uncertain 
you have to work out a strategy to survive said mrs nagy 
a 45yearold folklore specialist at the academy of sciences who is 
fluent in english and german i work about 70 to 80 hours a 
week 
her monthly net salary of about 135 after 20 years at the 
academy illustrates how the former communist regime treated most 
intellectuals who were not party members 
a few intellectuals got into the bureaucracy but most faced a 
combination of punishment for dissent and pay lower than that of 
bluecollar workers 
mrs nagy works as a parttime editor of folklore literature to 
supplement the family income and three of her four children take 
odd jobs for pocket money two boys study at budapest universities 
more liberty has been a mixed blessing to the nagys 
with democracy has come greater inflation now approaching a 
yearly rate of 20 percent also mrs nagy often has visiting 
mouths to feed because her husband is a hungarian from 
transylvania in neighboring romania and the revolution there has 
given his relatives freedom to travel 
in this situation i cant care too much about politics but 
one has to think that things will be getting better after all 
mrs nagy told an interviewer in her budapest apartment 
i see the political changes as terribly interesting but in 
our everyday life the situation has not changed you realize that 
with every month the economic situation worsens 
relatives arrive from transylvania in western romania in 
groups of three or four and stay for varying periods 
umpteen times its been like this the door bell rings and 
outside are our romanian relatives mrs nagy said my first 
thought always is the fridge is empty so is the purse but ive 
got to look after them 
vacations have been only a dream to the nagys for years but now 
even normal life is squeezed by price increases the twomonth 
electricity bill just went up from to 4600 florints about 74 
from less than 3000 
daniel nagy earned the equivalent of 177 a month as a chemical 
engineer for a state enterprise but his wife said its not clear 
what his income will be from the new partnership 
for a long time i havent bought a new dress she said 
most everything we wear has been bought at a secondhand shop 
to find something suitable there is fun of a kind it is also 
interesting because people who do their purchasing there are 
very poor those who have to eke out a living with very little 
money 
worsening economic conditions have impoverished onefifth of 
hungarys 107 million people hungarians generally seem to feel 
economic problems will be with them for a long time whatever a new 
democratic government does 
average monthly pay is the equivalent of 129 rent averages 16 
a month and a pair of womens shoes costs 48 milk is 32 cents a 
liter just over a quart a kilogram 22 pounds of butter is 
260 and a kilo of pork costs 4 
most price increases stemmed from the reduction or elimination 
of subsidies and other cuts in public spending needed to qualify 
for international monetary fund credits price hikes in january and 
early february led to public protests and budapests first public 
transport strike 
</TEXT>
