<TEXT>
at dawn on april 25 1915 allied soldiers 
waded onto the gallipoli peninsula in an invasion that would cost 
hundreds of thousands of lives and end in failure 
seventyfive years later veterans of the campaign government 
oficials and tourists will come from as far as australia and new 
zealand for a commemoration some turks liken to a second invasion 
all hotels and boarding houses have been fully booked for 
months said muzaffer ecemis governor of canakkale province which 
includes the dardanelles strait and the peninsula north of it 
visiting dignitaries will be housed on a cruise ship they 
include prime minister margaret thatcher of britain the prime 
minister and defense minister of australia new zealands governor 
general and delegations from france and west germany 
two australian warships and a submarine set out from sydney 
france and britain also are sending two warships each with 
military bands and honor guards 
in world war i the ottoman turkish empire was allied with 
germany and austria against britain its dominions france and 
russia 
about 70 veterans of gallipoli aged 91 to 103 will be the most 
honored guests 
australian newspaper reports said one veteran john mccleery of 
perth planned to celebrate his 103rd birthday at anzac cove 
the place where australian and new zealand soldiers landed on his 
28th birthday 
the object of the gallipoli campaign which military historians 
call the first combined naval and land operation of modern warfare 
was to open the turkish straits to russia capture istanbul then 
known as constantinople in the west and take the ottoman empire 
out of the war 
an allied naval effort to break through the dardanelles the 
ancient hellespont had been halted after the loss of three 
battleships 
turks held their own victory celebrations march 18 to mark the 
end of that battle when they stopped the british navy from 
reaching the marmara sea 
gallipoli then became a battleground for nine months until the 
invading forces were evacuated in december 1915 and january 1916 
half a million soldiers from britain france australia new 
zealand and india fought on the peninsula and more than half became 
casualties including 55000 killed in battle 10000 listed as 
missing and 21000 who died of disease mainly dysentary 
an equal number of turks were sent into battle estimates are 
that half were killed 
historians still debate the mistakes made and opportunities 
missed by both sides 
some say an allied victory would have shortened the long costly 
war by two or three years and prevented or delayed the bolshevik 
revolution in russia 
it was the only victory for the turks in world war i and 
provided the selfconfidence they needed to salvage a nation from 
the dismembered empire 
the battle also gave them a modern hero kemal ataturk who made 
his name as a military genius in gallipoli he later established 
turkey a predominantly moslem country as a secular republic with 
westernstyle laws 
australians celebrate each april 25 as a national holiday 
gallipoli was their first appearance on the global scene and 
historians say it gave them a sense of pride and nationhood 
britain and france now are allied with turkey in nato and 
australia is a valued trading partner thousands of turks have 
emigrated to australia 
huseyin goseler a turk and jane urwin an australian will 
join the celebrations by getting married april 25 at an old 
fortress that overlooks the dardanelles from the hills of 
gallipoli they said in a telephone interview 
just in time to serve the visitors they and another australian 
have opened bobs burger pub named for bob hawke prime minister 
of australia 
