<TEXT>
what has become of the social hall henry 
gruene built a century ago well the antique building now 
restored is where the girl scouts meet by day but at night it 
becomes a beer joint where a new generation of country musicians 
strut their stuff to stardom and the joint is jumping 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
by day this is a quiet little town 
overlooking the rocky guadalupe river travelers hunt for antiques 
eat barbecued brisket and laze around sipping cool drinks 
after dark is when the place comes alive and you have to think 
old henry gruene would approve 
after dark local regulars and the curious from the big city 
crowd into a centuryold saloon gruene hall sipping beer from 
longneck bottles and beating the boards to the sounds of the 
fabulous thunderbirds jerry jeff walker bo diddley and other 
bignames familiar to country music fans 
a lot of great sweaty nights happen here says 
singersongwriter hal ketchum leaning back in an old chair near 
the halls bar theres nothing like a good 105degree day in 
here with your band 
by day gruene hall is a meeting spot for girl scouts and 
debutantes but when the sun goes down it has become one of texas 
hippest honkytonks its pictured on album covers and serves as 
folksy stage set for videos and television specials 
like the music shrines of nashville gruene hall attracts 
thousands of music fans to this little village a historic district 
that has remained a community unto itself despite being 
incorporated into new braunfels a town of 22000 people a few 
miles up the road from san antonio 
henry gruene pronounced green for whom the town was named 
built the hall in the 1870s as a social center local farmers came 
to the hall to weigh their cotton before delivering it to the gin 
next door and on saturday nights brought their families there to 
dance bedding down their children next to the walls on the 
original hardwood floor 
the old woodburning stove remains as do decorative signs 
dating to the 1920s 
the hall and several other gruene buildings are owned by jane 
nalley of new braunfels and pat molak of san antonio molak bought 
the hall and reopened it 15 years ago after it had been in disuse 
for several decades 
it long has been a favorite haunt of countryandwestern blues 
rock and folk musicians and in the last few years gained some 
national renown 
country music connoisseurs will recognize the names george 
strait and june carter cash strait played here about once a month 
for six years before he became a star he returned in january to 
tape commercials promoting a tour 
june carter cash johnny cashs wife arrived in january with 
her three sisters to film a documentary about their musician 
mother maybelle carter 
despite gruene halls newfound glory owners molak and nalley 
keep it a laidback place no advance ticket sales no dressing 
rooms for the musicians no matter how big theyve become 
truth is gruene hall is a beer joint or as molak calls it a 
dive and a goodsized dive at that about 500 people crowd inside 
to dance and listen to a live perforsmance 
they have good concerts i know that for a town this small 
its amazing how they attract bigname people in here says john 
graves a 23yearold student at southwest texas state university 
in nearby san marcos who likes to hang out at gruene hall to shoot 
pool 
country singer and recent grammy winner rodney crowell heard 
about gruene hall and called one time wanting to play here ms 
nalley says 
another grammy winner lyle lovett also played the hall as 
have michael murphy delbert mcclinton gary p nunn and dozens of 
others whose pictures dot the walls near the bar 
hal ketchum 37 hopes to one day count himself among the famous 
who got their start in gruene hall where he was given his first 
chance to play one of his own songs in public now he and a 
fivepiece dance band play there about six times a year 
gruene hall he says was his music school a place where he was 
able to hear some of the greats 
theres a lot of old notes hanging in the air here he says 
