<TEXT>
the third district of budapest lying 
on the buda side is likely to be overlooked by the average visitor 
to the city although it adjoins the major tourist areas of the 
fishermens bastion and margaret island with its hot springs and 
luxury hotels 
it deserves a closer look it is a place where antiquity the 
nearer past and the present all come together 
if you take the boat upstream to the medieval town and 
presentday artistic center of szentendre youll be going past the 
third district much of the way the handy electric train known by 
its initials hev and costing about 10 cents goes right through the 
third district on the way to szentendre 
consider names of two of the train stations aquincum and roman 
furdo bath 
yes the romans were here they conquered the pannonians of 
illyrian stock in 9 ad and formed the province of pannonia 
later divided into upper and lower pannonia 
aquincum was the capital of lower pannonia and the layout of 
the town is still apparent showing outlines of the amphitheaters 
of the roman military town and the roman civil town including a 
pillared hall and the sites of some town houses the museum at the 
site contains statuary coins jewelry a waterorgan a jupiter 
column and other artifacts of aquincums roman days aquincum has 
hours like any other museum complex a check with your hotel or 
ibusz the hungarian tourist office is advised though much of it 
can be seen from the train and surrounding streets 
aquincum eventually formed the nucleus of obuda old buda 
which joined with buda and pest in the early 1870s to become 
budapest obuda according to tradition was the residence of 
attila the hun who in the fifth century won big concessions from 
the romans later in the ninth century arpad and the magyars took 
over the region and established the first dynasty of hungarian 
kings the town flourished in the middle ages and the remains of a 
palace for hungarian queens are still in evidence then came the 
turks and the town fell into decay germanspeaking settlers put 
it back on its feet in the 17th century 
much of budapest once was farmland and this is evident in the 
area between aquincum and the city line in bekamsmegyer highrise 
white box apartment blocks face streets of stuccoed old peasant 
houses with tile roofs and chimneys originally built to vent the 
big tile stoves that were a traditional source of heat in such 
houses here are orchards vegetable plots and enough crows for a 
midwestern corn field services still are held in the old church 
and the neighborhood restaurant operates in one of the old 
buildings with gypsy music to go with its tasty fare 
but then turn around and confront the present walking among the 
apartment houses with lobbies of unadorned concrete lit by raw 
lightbulbs upstairs the apartments are likely to be attractive 
and modern with traditional hungarian embroidered pillows on the 
couches and sofa beds that budapests housing shortage mandates in 
every living room traditional plates painted with flowers may hang 
on the walls sometimes clashing with those hung by the younger 
set decorated with distorted faces and the word punk 
during the most recent christmas season many families sat up 
until midnight beside their lighted trees listening to the 
television news of the government upset in romania many of the 
older generation came from or have relatives in transylvania where 
romanias hungarian minority lives 
on a typical day shoppers go early in the morning to the 
supermarket in bekasmegyer to get fresh rolls for breakfast and buy 
their days supply of coffee beans which they grind on the spot 
in the evening highrise dwellers walk their dogs 
this is a blue collar district where young people go off to 
work with computers in the government as accountants or even as 
rock musicians many older people work too even if its only 
selling their embroidery 
roman antiquities seem far away but theyre just down the road 
the jampacked hev train taking commuters to work at 6 am will 
pass between one of the aquincum amphitheaters and the remains of a 
roman wall 
</TEXT>
