an estimated 150000 americans will visit 
china this year though more than twice that many were projected 
for 1990 before last years disturbances in beijing 
to offset the drop chinas national tourism office is working 
to lure more visitors with new itineraries according to peter 
cheung vice president and general manager of campc china express a 
tour wholesaling company based in san francisco 
the hulunbir grasslands itinerary will let travelers visit 
mongolia while others into northeast china offer visits to the ice 
and snow festivals at cities like harbin the restored old summer 
palace located in the mountains near beijing a new art and 
antique bazaar in the capital city and a theatrical museum in 
tianjin also are in place in time for this years travelers 
domestic airline fare hikes will spur a rise of about 20 percent 
in tour prices says cheung he estimates that a typical twoweek 
tour of the country will cost about 19002000 including 
airfare hotel meals sightseeing transfers and baggage handling 
he advises prospective visitors to study travel material before 
making firm plans besides guidebooks travelers can get maps 
brochures and planning materials from the china national tourist 
office 60 e 42nd st suite 3126 new york ny 10165 
