<DOCNO> AP900402-0227 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
weight watchers magazine which devotes its july issue to 
travel provides some advice for keeping the fat out of your 
vacation while leaving the fun in 
plan ahead request special meals while buying plane tickets 
for example 
with regular airplane food scrape the sauce off the entree 
have one or two bites and eat the bread dont pour dressing on 
the salad but dip the fork into the dressing then eat some salad 
for long flights take snacks from home like fresh fruit or 
vegetables sealed in plastic bags and stay out of the airport 
snack shops if your flight is delayed 
choose one realistic goal for the trip like splitting 
desserts 
for car travel pack a small cooler with diet sodas iced tea 
bottled water individual cereal boxes yogurt fruits and 
vegetables for crunchier snacks bring popcorn 
in restaurants order sauce on the side to control the amount 
you eat ask for fresh fruit with whipped topping for dessert or 
split a dessert with someone else if youre having pizza have it 
plain and skip the sausage pepperoni and other greasy toppings 
if you do eat heavily one day go light the next with a little 
bit of protein and some carbohydrates include fruits and 
vegetables and drink plenty of water 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP900402-0228 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
heres a word of advice about taking 
your pet with you on your vacation 
dont 
vacations arent for pets says dr ken clever professor of 
veterinary medical technology at wilson college they and you 
will be happier if you place them in a good boarding facility or 
with a trusted friend or family member 
motion sickness and heat exhaustion are the most likely problems 
your pet will encounter according to clever and other odder 
dangers can come up he recalls treating a dog that had been 
dragged a halfmile on an interstate highway because the owner had 
tied it to the bumper of his car during a rest stop and then forgot 
about it 
if you insist on taking your pet then plan for accommodating 
the animal on the road 
take your pet on a test ride or two before the trip to determine 
if it will get motion sickness this problem is very common with 
dogs and cats your veterinarian can prescribe a medication to 
prevent vomiting he adds that its not a good idea to medicate 
an animal on a justincase basis 
you may also find that cats sometimes get a little excited on 
trips he says the veterinarian can advise you about sedatives 
for overly active pets 
plan adequate room for the animal to move around you 
shouldnt stuff a pet into an already crowded car nor should you 
keep the animal in the front seat where the animal could distract 
the driver he says the back seat is the safest spot since 
theres no way to secure a pet with a seat belt 
if you must leave your pet in the car roll the windows down a 
bit this may seem like obvious advice clever says but many 
owners forget and their pets suffer heat exhaustion 
another problem is accommodation since many places wont take 
pets you will have to map out the trip more closely than usual to 
assure a place to stay clever suggests campgrounds since more of 
them welcome pets 
before you go be sure your pets vaccinations are up to date 
this protects the animal from diseases in new places and it 
protects you legally when you travel to a state with different 
regulations the doctor recommends taking your pets health 
certification records along as a minimum youll need proof of 
rabies vaccination if your pet bites someone during the trip 
international regulations are usually much more stringent so check 
them before you leave 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

