<TEXT>
editors note george bria retired from the ap in 1981 after 40 
years that included coverage of world war ii from italy 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
asparagus has sublime flavor beauty 
lineage in a word class and a gardner who achieves a 
wellestablished bed gets respect 
a wouldbe asparagus grower needs patience and determination it 
takes a good five years to have harvests worth talking about 
in a mobile society this eliminates a lot of people whos 
going to plant a vegetable for some future tenant to enjoy but if 
youve settled down or retired an asparagus bed is a giltedged 
investment producing abundantly and requiring little effort to 
maintain 
asparagus ranks as one of the oldest vegetables little 
different in its cultivated state from the wild spears of remote 
ages menus recovered from the ruins of pompeii show the romans 
enjoyed young asparagus as a spring delicacy 
my own 21yearold patch a mere child in the annals of 
asparagus longevity yielded 702 fat thin and mediumsize spears 
in 1989 586 in 1988 and 607 in 1987 thats a lot of asparagus out 
of a 15by10foot bed more than the needs of my wife and me and 
we gave much of it to our neighboring son 
in terms of waiting think of asparagus as an apple tree or 
blueberry bush unlike most vegetables which you plant anew every 
year asparagus is perennial after youve first dug in the roots 
they bear year after year european chronicles tell of 100yearold 
asparagus beds bestowed as dowries in marriage contracts 
asparagus thrives everywhere in the united states except areas 
of the deep south and west where winters are too mild in my 
garden 50 miles north of new york city asparagus starts coming up 
in late april and yields continuously until midjune then i stop 
cutting and let the spears grow to handsome ferns as tall as eight 
feet which feed the roots for next years crop 
one of the joys of asparagus is its early arrival youve hardly 
started getting the rest of the garden ready for summer and here 
you are harvesting a delicious vegetable another plus is that the 
spears come up a few at a time thus you have prolonged harvests 
once out of the ground a spear grows incredibly fast as much 
as 10 inches in a day six to eight inches is a good cutting 
height after that the spears get woody at the base 
asparagus may be grown from seed but you save time by planting 
roots acquired at nurseries or seed houses worldwide about 35 
varieties are cultivated in the united states the best known are 
mary and martha washington introduced early this century recently 
new allmale cultivars with names like jersey giant have appeared 
and are getting good reviews for larger yields and better disease 
resistance 
because of the time involved in establishing a bed however it 
wouldnt be practical for some of us to experiment with different 
varieties my martha washington keeps producing generously ill 
leave new cultivars to new gardeners 
the most work youll probably ever do with asparagus comes at 
the start in planting the roots in early spring in a 
welltilled sunny spot you dig trenches about a foot deep and a 
foot wide in rows about three feet apart pack the bottom of the 
trenches with wellrotted manure or compost mounding this up and 
spread the roots over the mounds about two feet apart then you 
bury the roots leaving the crowns two to three inches below the 
surface sixteen roots should be plenty for a family of three 
in this first year youll get some thin spears leave these 
alone too you can start cutting the third year but it will be a 
while after that before you have a really prolific bed 
in the meantime your biggest problem will be weeds how do you 
remove them without disturbing the asparagus roots i solved this 
by mulching the bed with a couple of inches of salt hay obtainable 
in bales from nurseries the mulch stifles weeds but allows spears 
to come through then it decomposes into fine compost helping the 
fertility of the bed i put on a bale a year 
in the middle of june when i stop cutting i push the mulch 
aside and spread some fertilizer around the spears then i push the 
mulch back on except for a little dusting to deal with insects 
thats all i do the ferns die back in the fall and i wait for the 
cycle to begin again with that first great taste of newborn 
asparagus next april 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP900402-0241 </DOCNO>
