<TEXT>
young adults see their grandparents as a 
stabilizing factor during times of family trouble especially 
grandchildren from singleparent households according to a survey 
of college students 
grandparenthood today is a very present aspect in family life 
not only for young children but for young adults as well gregory 
e kennedy of central missouri state university reported 
kennedy surveyed 704 college students under age 23 in 1988 and 
found that students tended to feel closer to their mothers parents 
than to their fathers parents they also tended to be closer to 
grandmothers than to grandfathers 
the results were reported in the february issue of the 
gerontologist published by the gerontological society of america 
ten percent of those who felt closest to a grandmother 
identified their relationship as intimately close while 26 
percent said very close and 28 percent said close 
four percent of those who felt closest to a grandfather said 
their relationship was intimately close with 15 percent saying 
they were very close and 21 percent saying they were close 
when family background was analyzed the survey results 
suggested singleparent and blended families experienced 
grandparents as being more involved and influential in their family 
than did students from intact families the study said 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
americas elderly are losing ground 
financially as rising health care costs consume everlarger shares 
of their income according to a study by the house select committee 
on aging 
the report said any advantage that the elderly may have by 
entering retirement with higher incomes than a decade ago will be 
quickly lost as health and longterm care costs absorb larger 
portions of their income 
while virtually all lower and middleincome americans feel 
some pressure from these costs the problem is acute for people 
whose incomes rise no faster than overall inflation said 
committee chairman edward r roybal dcalif 
the report found that people retiring in any given year will see 
healthcare costs rise more than 1 times faster than their income 
outofpocket health care costs rose from 123 percent of elderly 
income in 1977 to 182 percent in 1988 it said 
all indications are that this trend of costs outpacing income 
will continue into the foreseeable future and that health costs are 
likely to reach 20 percent of elderly income by the early 1990s 
the study said 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
elderly 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
the government has issued guidelines to help 
ensure that new drugs are adequately tested to determine their 
effects on older people 
there is widespread agreement that many drugs even those 
likely to be used in the elderly have not always been extensively 
studied in elderly patients the food and drug administration 
said in a public notice as a consequence there has often been 
little information available to guide therapy in such patients 
the agency issued guideline for the study of drugs likely to 
be used in the elderly 
the publicaton was welcomed by rep thomas downey dny who 
said they were overdue given growing concerns about mismedication 
and drug misuse among the elderly 
the health and welfare of millions of older americans depends 
on a serious commitment by the fda to ensure that available drug 
therapy is safe and effective downey said 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
editors copies of the guidelines may be obtained by submitting 
a written request and two selfaddressed adhesive labels to the 
legislative professional and consumer affairs branch hfd365 
center for drug evaluation and research food and drug 
