<TEXT>
corporate raiders and junk bond traders arent 
the only ones to hit some rough bumps makers of stretch 
limousines a power symbol in the statusconscious 1980s are 
struggling as demand has shifted into low gear 
stretch limousine production has dropped off from the boom times 
during the reagan years when production jumped from about 2500 
limousines a year in 1980 to a peak of about 7000 in 1987 
some 57 coachbuilding companies including two in the chicago 
area now stretch only about 5700 limousines a year according to 
limousine and chauffeur the industry trade magazine 
stretch limousines were an ostentatious symbol of wealth in the 
money decade of the 1980s 
some corporations were spending up to 20000 a week on 
roundtheclock limo service said wayne smith executive 
director of the national limousine association in washington dc 
executives were doing multibilliondollar deals and the limo 
service played a role in beefing up the companys image he said 
but a slower economy troubles in the junkbond market the 
savings and loan fiasco and a slowdown in mergers and acquisitions 
all have contributed to cuts in corporate limousine service some 
budgetminded companies are trying to prune expensive frills 
the ostentatious look just isnt good for the corporate image 
anymore said joseph v scaletta president of moloney 
coachbuilders in chicago 
sales are down about 25 percent at moloney which makes about 
450 stretch limos a year scaletta attributes the drop to 
overbuilding 
but scaletta believes it is still possible to find other markets 
executives arent going for the superstretches anymore 
said scaletta but now that we are adding cellular phones fax 
machines and even small computers they see the benefit of having a 
traveling office 
another chicagoarea manufacturer limousine werks of 
schaumburg says it has looked to the foreign market 
company president matthew baines says sales are up 28 percent 
over last year in part due to a recent contract to make stretch 
cadillac limousines for japan he estimates production at about 
one a day 
the first limousine was a model g made in 1908 by cadillac said 
dave john cadillac fleet director in detroit 
in the 1960s as buyers increasingly demanded custom flourishes 
the major auto makers stopped customizing limousines and 
independent companies known as coach builders entered the scene 
these companies buy cadillacs lincoln continentals or other 
luxury cars as a coach builder package without a roof then 
they cut the cars in half stretch them by 8 inches to as much as 
100plus inches and fill them with whatever luxuries customers 
want from televisions and minibars to chandeliers and hot tubs 
a cadillac brougham at limousine werks costs from 53000 to 
62000 mercedes go for 135000 and armored cars start at 
100000 
changing times also have affected companies offering limousine 
service the airport trade is now their breadandbutter so they 
are positioning themselves as an affordable alternative to a taxi 
the airport trade accounts for 80 percent of the rides provided 
by the american limousine corp of suburban burr ridge which has a 
fleet of 150 cars said owner george jacobs who is also president 
of the national limousine association 
but jacobs believes the limousine will always stand for luxury 
and romance 
he recalls one young suitor who ordered two limousines when he 
wanted to propose to his girlfriend 
