<TEXT>
columbia savings amp loan 
association the oncehigh flying thrift that invested billions of 
dollars in highrisk junk bonds says it lost 379 million in the 
fourth quarter and 200 million during the first two months of this 
year and is now insolvent 
the disclosure on sunday increases the prospects for an 
expensive federal bailout 
columbia had been one of the nations most profitable sampls due 
to its large portfolio of highyielding junk bonds many of which 
were bought from michael milken and his securities firm the 
nowdefunct drexel burnham lambert group inc 
in the mid1980s columbias annual earnings approached 200 
million 
but the deterioration in the junk bond market over the past 
several months has forced columbia to write off much its holdings 
resulting in huge losses 
columbia said it lost 379 million or 1917 a share in the 
final quarter of 1989 compared to earnings of 16 million or 37 
cents a share in 1988 losses for the entire year came to 591 
million or 3011 a share vs net income of 65 million or 149 
per share the previous year 
the losses reflect junk bondrelated loss provisions and 
writedowns of about 500 million in the fourth quarter 
the company said that its shareholders equity or the firms 
value to its stockholders fell to minus 121 million at feb 28 
1990 rendering columbia insolvent under generally accepted 
accounting principles just three months earlier columbia had 
equity of 776 million 
in a statement columbia said it expected significant 
additional loss reserves and other asset writedowns will occur in 
march 1990 it said it had a loss of nearly 200 million in the 
first two months of 1990 because of further problems in the junk 
bond market 
but columbia is hoping to avoid federal receivership by 
liquidating its junk bond holdings 
we have initiated programs to reduce overhead significantly 
and to improve our traditional thrift operations edward g 
harshfield the thrifts newly appointed chief exectuvie said in a 
statement sunday 
between august and february columbia sold about 575 million in 
junk bonds and other securities according to the company 
federal regulators had imposed restrictions on columbia in 
november because of problems with its 38 billion junkbond 
portfolio had caused the thrifts capital to be substantially 
inadequate the office of thrift supervision restricted among 
other things columbias growth dividend payment and loan funding 
lending is now limited to residential loans not exceeding 500000 
columbias assets for 1989 totaled 93 billion down from 127 
billion in 1988 the thrift has 950 employees in 29 southern 
california offices 
