<TEXT>
spending on residential nonresidential and 
government construction projects all increased in february the 
government said monday helped for the second straight month by 
mild weather over much of the country 
the commerce department said construction spending rose 26 
percent to a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 4365 billion 
that followed a revised 25 percent jump in january which first 
had been reported to have been a 18 percent gain 
spending in december the fourth coldest on record had slipped 
03 percent and analysts attributed the subsequent improvement to 
warm temperatures 
warm weather certainly is helping said steven cochran an 
economist with wefa group in bala cynwyd pa if it had been 
cold we wouldnt have seen these figures im sure 
but david berson chief economist with the federal national 
mortgage association in washington said construction spending 
began to lose its seasonal benefit in march 
we expect it to start leveling off if not decline because it 
will no longer have the seasonal boost and also because of 
increasing interest rates berson said 
residential construction spending rose 17 percent in february 
to a 1985 billion annual rate after gaining 29 percent in 
january 
