<DOCNO> AP900402-0262 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the us industrial sector remained weak in 
march but declined at its slowest rate since june a possible 
indication that the overall economy may be poised for a pickup 
according to a survey of the nations purchasing managers released 
monday 
the national association of purchasing management which tracks 
economic trends by polling its members said its overall index rose 
to 488 percent in march from 483 percent the previous month 
a reading below 50 indicates the manufacturing economy generally 
is declining above 50 that it generally is expanding 
the march index represented the 11th consecutive monthly decline 
but was at its highest level since junes 488 percent reading due 
to an increase in production and new export orders the tempe 
arizbased trade group said in its report 
with the exception of january the purchasing managers index 
has risen gradually every month since november leading some 
economists to speculate the economy may have bottomed out 
its not so much the economy is getting strong but somewhat 
steadier said robert a brusca chief financial economist for 
nikko securities co international the report raises speculation 
that the worst of the declining phase is behind us the 
question remains how strong and sustainable the statistical rebound 
is 
robert j bretz chairman of the purchasing managers business 
survey committee said the slight increase in the index may be 
signaling a levelingoff in the 11month decline in the economy 
the continued easing in the pace of the economic decline as we 
exit the first quarter is encouraging said bretz who also is 
director of materials management at stamford connbased pitney 
bowes inc 
although we may be forming a bottom caution should be 
exercised since the first robin never makes it a spring 
maury harris chief economist for painewebber inc said that 
although manufacturing makes up a large portion of the nations 
gross national product there are other areas that remain sluggish 
the construction industry is getting ready to tumble he 
said 
a report released monday by the commerce department said 
construction spending rose 26 percent in february compared with a 
revised 25 percent gain in january 
harris attributed the increase solely to unusually warm weather 
across much of the nation and said the industrys overall 
fundamentals were poor 
the production portion of the purchasing managers survey 
increased for the second consecutive month during march it rose to 
an 11month high of 544 percent from 515 percent in february 
new orders grew slightly in march but at a slower pace than in 
february when they increased for the first time since mid1989 
the new orders index stood at 504 percent down from 518 percent 
new export orders also rose the group said the seasonally 
unadjusted new export orders index was 595 percent up from 530 
percent and the highest level since september 1989 
imports increased for the third consecutive month the number of 
members importing in march inched up to 78 percent from 77 percent 
the group said 
but the employment portion of the survey declined for the 13th 
consecutive month with the index falling to 452 percent from 467 
percent members continued to report layoffs hiring freezes and 
early retirement programs to reduce employment 
supplier deliveries were faster for the 11th consecutive month 
the group said most commodities were in supply with the exception 
of bearings electric motors and some chemicals it said 
meanwhile prices of goods fell for the 10th consecutive month 
although the pace of decline was lower than in february 
the purchasing managers report is based on a monthly survey of 
purchasing executives at over 300 industrial companies most of the 
figures are adjusted for seasonal factors 
</TEXT>
