the shellshocked tokyo stock exchange was hammered 
again monday as speculation that major institutional investors were 
getting ready to dump stocks triggered the markets secondworst 
decline ever 
the yen also tumbled against the dollar worsening the stock 
market selloff in a violent twin reaction to an unconfirmed news 
report that major life insurers planned to shift funds out of the 
stock market 
the bellwether nikkei stock average of 225 issues dropped 
197838 points or 659 percent to 2800207 the plunge was 
second only to the oct 20 1987 drop that followed wall streets 
black monday crash and saw the nikkei fall 383648 points or 
149 percent 
the index rebounded more than 400 points early tuesday morning 
but quickly resumed its slump and finished the morning session down 
7719 points or 028 percent at 2792488 
the influential financial daily nihon keizai shimbun reported 
monday that major insurance firms including daiichi mutual life 
insurance co nippon life insurance co and sumitomo mutual life 
insurance co planned to sell large blocks of shares the 
newspaper said the sales were required because the ratio of the 
insurors stock holdings to total assets was approaching government 
regulatory limits 
daiichi told a midday news conference that it would continue 
to buy stocks during its current fiscal year but the report 
already had shaken the markets 
the big life insurers are the markets most conservative 
longterm and richest investors the report saying massive selling 
was likely scared off potential buyers said christopher 
leighton manager of international sales at schroder securities 
japan ltd 
although finance ministry officials and daiichi denied the 
report it reaffirmed market expectations of a general shift by 
major investors out of the stock market said jason james 
strategist at james capel pacific ltd 
the initial price declines snowballed amid rapid brokerage 
selling for individuals who needed cash to meet margin calls and on 
profittaking by investors highpriced electrical company shares 
traders said 
also weakening the stock market was the continued decline of the 
yen which is seen as worsening inflation prospects and chasing 
japanese investment funds to ovrseas markets 
